‚ÄúMy brother and I were adopted at three months old, we are twins . We were born in an orphanage in Bogota, Colombia. My adoptive parents are Polish and Italian and they flew down to Colombia to adopt since the process was taking too long in the US. When they arrived at the orphanage, they were sat in a room and presented with babies that needed adoption. They had already seen two other babies before they saw my brother and I. My parents told me they knew right away, my mom said ‚ÄúThose are my babies.‚Äù It took about two weeks to finish the adaptation process then we were off to south Jersey. Growing up we had two birthdays. One was our special birthday which was the day were were adopted and one on the day we were born. So I always knew I was adopted. My parents made sure we knew where we were born and that we were special. I was fortunate enough to have a great childhood and extremely tight knit family. My parents adopted another set of twins girls from the orphanage and another baby from the US. Being adopting gave me a  great disposition of gratitude in life. When my family went back to visit the orphanage Thirty years later, I saw how the children lived. It was beautifully heartbreaking. Seeing all those babies and children that needed a home. Knowing that the older you get in an orphanage the odds of being adopted grow less and less. People always ask me, ‚ÄúWould you like to meet your birth mom and dad?‚Äù I would, to thank them for allowing me to be in a loving family that has been supportive since day one, a family that has provide multiple siblings, and a family that has provided a sense of roots.‚Äù
.

node.text: This trip was from NY to Seattle so my mom could visit HER mom for a while.  It was a long night getting from Virginia to NY on the train so we could catch our morning flight.  I was SO happy when we got to the terminal at #JFK... my mom brought me up to the rooftop area that my favorite airline, #JetBlue, has for working dogs like me to take a break and play.  I had fun crossing my paws to ask for my ball, then returning it to my mom.  I could play that game all day, but I had to get my mom on the plane on time!  Thanks JetBlue for having a great place for me to hang out (well, and for people too). When my mom decides on our travel, things like that always come into "play!" Deep in the Colombian jungle is the Cuidad Perdida, the Lost City, founded over a thousand years ago and inhabited by between two and eight thousand people in it‚Äôs heyday. It‚Äôs situated high on the mountainsides, bathed in sunshine and regular torrential tropical rain. These flat round areas in the photo would have held wooden houses in their time used for lodging, or for gatherings. This view is just a fragment of the extensive and very haunting remains of this city abandoned during the 1500s and left for treasure hunters ever since.

Slight sob story so stay with me. 6 months ago to the day I broke my leg in multiple places. I had quit my job in anticipation of starting my new career with JetBlue. As it turned out, my leg had other plans. My flight attendant career was put on hold. I was super sad but could not wait to start training. That day finally came last month and I had the opportunity to meet 33 other amazing people who we embarked on a month long intense training. It definitely had its ups and downs, but I am proud to say I am now a JetBlue Inflight Crew-member! Shoutout to the lifelong friends I made and finally earning my wings! .
